00:34:19.199 --> 00:34:22.719
So I'm just wondering like what advice would you give to a team or an organization

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:26.439
who's struggling to go from, okay, we have a model and it fits well enough.

00:34:26.439 --> 00:34:30.399
And it's sort of doing what we want it to do, uh, to having a model in production

00:34:30.399 --> 00:34:33.800
that we're using regularly and that we, that we depend on that it feels like a

00:34:33.800 --> 00:34:39.000
very big change to me, uh, psychologically for the team or the organization to go

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:43.919
from, you know, yes, we can do this to, uh, yes, we, we are relying on this thing

00:34:43.919 --> 00:34:45.600
and it is in production as important to us.

00:34:45.840 --> 00:34:47.639
So, so what advice do you have for, for people who are

00:34:47.639 --> 00:34:48.679
struggling to make that step?

00:34:49.080 --> 00:34:49.399
Yeah.

00:34:49.399 --> 00:34:49.760
Yeah.

00:34:50.000 --> 00:34:54.760
So I think one thing is to acknowledge, to understand that you, you as a team or

00:34:54.760 --> 00:35:00.399
some part of the team is going to need to, um, gain some new skills is going to need

00:35:00.399 --> 00:35:05.800
to learn how to do some new things and to try to make space and understand that,

00:35:05.840 --> 00:35:10.159
that, that kind of, that kind of change is, is coming and is needed.

00:35:10.360 --> 00:35:15.080
So this is, um, for example, uh, you know, you know, like maybe it's important for

00:35:15.080 --> 00:35:22.479
someone on your team to start in, in like kind of learning, like what does our org

00:35:22.520 --> 00:35:26.000
need if I were to employ a model, like what is going to work for our org?

00:35:26.040 --> 00:35:30.080
Uh, so this is now working with maybe people who are DevOps-y, maybe

00:35:30.080 --> 00:35:34.399
people who are, I sit in IT, like, like what do, so, so what are

00:35:34.399 --> 00:35:37.120
the new skills we need to, um, add?

00:35:37.520 --> 00:35:41.040
Uh, so that's, that's one thing is to acknowledge that if you have been

00:35:41.040 --> 00:35:45.800
very statistically focused and it's time to deploy a model, how can we make space

00:35:45.800 --> 00:35:51.000
for some proportion of our team to, to gain some of those, um, some of those skills?

00:35:51.199 --> 00:35:56.280
I think also to not be afraid of some of those tools and skills and to, um,

00:35:56.320 --> 00:36:02.520
understand that like, that's how you, um, scale the impact of your work.

00:36:02.520 --> 00:36:07.959
So, so for example, like to learn, um, you know, about Docker, right?

00:36:07.959 --> 00:36:12.679
Like to learn about, um, um, uh, like, like what, like what in your,

00:36:12.719 --> 00:36:13.679
how do things work in your org?

00:36:13.679 --> 00:36:18.719
If your org has like a, like a certain cloud platform that they, that you, that

00:36:18.719 --> 00:36:22.800
you all use, like to start to, to not so much be like, okay, yes, well, we're the

00:36:22.800 --> 00:36:26.840
data people that they, we live, work in this environment, but to start to kind

00:36:26.840 --> 00:36:30.639
of push again, like to find how do I go?

00:36:30.679 --> 00:36:32.600
How do I then take that next step?

00:36:32.959 --> 00:36:37.159
Also, I think doing things in as small of way as possible.

00:36:37.159 --> 00:36:43.560
So like you can, um, if you're going to deploy some kind of a model as, um,

00:36:43.679 --> 00:36:48.679
like, like as an API, it's like, it doesn't have to the first time you do

00:36:48.679 --> 00:36:54.879
it, be the huge scalable, can go to infinity kind of API.

00:36:55.000 --> 00:36:58.959
Like you can first do a, um, API at all.

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:01.760
And then you show you, you know, like a software engineer or

00:37:01.760 --> 00:37:06.320
DevOps-y kind of coworker, like, look, look, if we serve this in this way,

00:37:06.520 --> 00:37:09.800
then we, you can get predictions back in this way and then have a discussion

00:37:09.800 --> 00:37:12.239
about like, how can we start to, to scale that up?

00:37:12.239 --> 00:37:17.320
So I think the first thing is to think about, um, the skills that people need.

00:37:17.320 --> 00:37:18.959
Someone needs to gain a little bit.

00:37:19.000 --> 00:37:23.520
The second thing is to think about, um, infrastructure and like,

00:37:23.879 --> 00:37:26.800
like your, the tools you use now, how are they different from

00:37:26.800 --> 00:37:27.800
the tools that are being there?

00:37:27.800 --> 00:37:30.479
Like, what can you learn about your internal specifics?

00:37:30.679 --> 00:37:34.719
And then also going back to that, like iterative, like do something as small

00:37:34.719 --> 00:37:39.520
as possible to show and be like, okay, how can we make, take that, take that next step.

